\begin{abstract}
We study the equilibrium and nonequilibrium properties of two qubits interacting through a polariton bus with an ultrastrong coupled qubit-cavity system. By tuning the energy gap of the qubits maintaining the polariton within the vacuum, we demonstrate an improvement of two-qubit gate operation time and excitations transfer as the ultrastrong coupling strength is increased. Our proposal might pave the way for multipurpose parity protected quantum information tasks, and for the enhancement of excitations transfer in disordered systems.

\end{abstract}

\pacs{03.65.Yz, 03.67.Lx, 42.50.Ct, 42.50.Pq}

\maketitle

{\em Introduction.---}Light-matter interaction in the strong coupling regime lies at the root of numerous advances in quantum technologies and  quantum information tasks~\cite{Ladd2010}. Recent experiments in solid state physics have reported the interaction between a two-level system (qubit) and an optical/microwave cavity~\cite{Vahala2003} attaining an unprecedent coupling strength known as the ultrastrong coupling (USC) regime~\cite{Ana2009,Gunter2009,Todorov2010,Scalari2012,Pol2010,Niemczyk2010}.  This regime has since been studied extensively from a theoretical viewpoint~\cite{Carusotto2005,Carusotto2006,Devoret2007,Bourassa2009,Hagen2010,Nataf2010,Doucot2005,Nataf2011,Kyaw2015,Felicetti2015,Lolli2015,rossatto2015}. In the USC regime, the coupling strength is comparable to the cavity and the qubit frequencies and, in the dipolar approximation, it is described by the quantum Rabi model (QRM)~\cite{Rabi1936,Braak2011} which exhibits a discrete ${\mathbb{Z}}_2$ symmetry, also called parity symmetry~\cite{Doucot2005}. The latter implies that low-lying eigenstates of the QRM, termed as polariton states, contain virtual excitations that cannot escape from the cavity~\cite{Carusotto2006}. It has also been demonstrated that these polariton states might be used as parity protected two-level systems for quantum computation~\cite{Nataf2011} and for quantum memory~\cite{Kyaw2015}. 

Apart from the fundamental interest in light-matter interaction under the USC regime, its potential for speeding up quantum information processing at subnanosecond time scales have been propounded in several recent theoretical investigations~\cite{Wang2004,Wang2009,Chang2011,Romero2012,KyawCluster} using circuit quantum electrodynamics (QED)~\cite{Blais2004}. In particular, Refs.~\cite{Romero2012,KyawCluster} proposed the use of a tunable qubit-cavity coupling strength to perform ultrafast two-qubit gates~\cite{Borja2010}. However, the main drawback in some of these proposals is the strong crosstalk among magnetic fluxes applied to the qubit with these complicated flux qubit architectures. In spite of the many challenges and difficulties encountered  with a light-matter system in the USC regime, henceforth called {\em polariton}, two recent proposals have shown that the interaction between the polariton and an ancillary qubit, with a biased energy-splitting, may allow for quantum state engineering and tomography~\cite{Felicetti2015}, and vacua characterization~\cite{Lolli2015} of light-matter systems in the USC regime. The idea of the ancillary qubit is extended to probe the spectral properties of complex systems~\cite{Modi2015}. Thus, we stress that the polariton-qubit interaction with tunable energy gaps for the ancilla might serve as a tool for implementing quantum information that preserves the parity symmetry.     

Here, we propose a USC system capable of acting as a polariton bus that mediates the interaction between qubits. Our proposal presents the following characteristics: (i) Improvement of two-qubit gate operation time with an increase in the qubit-cavity coupling strength in the polariton ($g_p/\omega_{\rm cav}$). (ii) The entangling gate is performed simply by biasing the qubits energy gap for fixed polariton parameters, thus overcoming the problem of tunable qubit-cavity coupling~\cite{Romero2012,KyawCluster}. (iii) Manipulation of the energy gap of qubits preserves the ${\mathbb{Z}}_2$ symmetry. (iv) Improvement in the rate of excitation transfer to qubit 2, see Fig.~\ref{Fig1}, with respect to an increase in $g_p/\omega_{\text{cav}}$, is possible even though qubit 1 is incoherently pumped. Therefore, our proposal might pave the way for multipurpose parity protected quantum information, and it may serve as a building block for the cavity-enhanced excitons transport in disordered many-body systems~\cite{Pupillo2015}. 
