{\em The model.---}Our model is depicted in Fig.~\ref{Fig1}. It consists of a qubit-cavity system interacting in the ultrastrong coupling regime that constitutes the polariton. The latter is described by the quantum Rabi model~\cite{Rabi1936,Braak2011}

nexttext:

Notice that our system exhibits a discrete ${\mathbb{Z}}_2$ symmetry associated with the parity operator ${\bm P}_N=(-1)^Ne^{i\pi b^\dag b}\bigotimes_{i=1}^N{\bm\sigma}_i^z$ where $N$ is the qubits number. As previously mentioned, this symmetry allows for parity protected quantum computing~\cite{Doucot2005,Nataf2011}, and quantum memory~\cite{Kyaw2015} in the USC regime.  

We now study the static and dynamical properties of the Hamiltonian~(\ref{HTotal}) as a function of the qubits energy gaps, $\omega_{q1}$ and $\omega_{q2}$, for fixed parameters of the polariton. This is a realistic situation that could be implemented in circuit QED, where qubits energy level spacing can be tuned via external magnetic fluxes~\cite{Nori2008}. Notice that when varying the qubits energy gap, the ${\mathbb{Z}}_2$ symmetry of the Hamiltonian~(\ref{HTotal}) remains unchanged. Moreover, it will allow us to achieve an Ising-type qubit-qubit interaction mediated by the polariton.

{\em Results.---}We begin our discussion with the simplest case of two identical qubits interacting with the polariton. In this case, the Hilbert space of the whole system is spanned by tensor products of the polariton eigenbasis $\{|j\rangle\}$ ($j=0,1,\hdots,\infty$), and the symmetric Dicke states $\{|D_{N,k}\rangle\}$ with $N=2$ qubits and $k=0,1,2$ excitations number, namely, $|D_{2,0}\rangle=|gg\rangle$, $|D_{2,1}\rangle=(|eg\rangle+|ge\rangle)/\sqrt{2}$, and $|D_{2,2}\rangle=|ee\rangle$. Figure~\ref{Fig2}(a) shows the lowest energy states as a function of the qubits energy gap $\omega_{q1}\!=\!\omega_{q2}\!=\!\Delta$ for parameters $\omega_{\rm cav}=1$, $\omega_p=0.8\omega_{\rm cav}$, $g_p=0.3\omega_{\rm cav}$, and $g_1\!=\!g_2\!=\!0.02\omega_{\rm cav}$. Here, as the energy gap of qubits approaches the energy of the polariton, the spectrum shows avoided level crossings between states that belong to the same parity subspace, red (squared) lines for even parity $(p=+1)$ and yellow (continuous) lines for odd parity $(p=-1)$, where $p$ stands for the eigenvalue of the parity operator ${\bm P}_N$. Moreover, there are straight lines that represent the states ${\vert {j} \rangle}{\vert {\psi} \rangle}$, where ${\vert {\psi} \rangle}=({\vert {eg} \rangle}-{\vert {ge} \rangle})/\sqrt{2}$ stands for the singlet state that does not couple to the polariton. In realistic situations, this antisymmetric state does not appear in spectroscopy measurements~\cite{Urbina2013,Urbina2015}. 

Furthermore, it is also apparent that the single polariton energy spectrum is recovered when $\Delta=0$ in Fig.~\ref{Fig2}(a), see Fig.~\ref{Fig2}(c) for comparison with the polariton spectrum. Figure~\ref{Fig2}(a) shows the labelling of lowest energy states as tensor products of polariton and two-qubit states $\{|j\rangle|D_{N,k}\rangle\}$. At the first avoided level crossing, for the resonance condition $\Delta=0.6042\omega_{\rm cav}$, both systems become maximally entangled, and hence they can exchange excitations. In particular, the states ${\vert {0} \rangle}{\vert {D_{2,1}} \rangle}$ and ${\vert {1} \rangle}{\vert {D_{2,0}} \rangle}$ exhibit population inversion as shown in Fig.~\ref{Fig2}(b). Notice that ${\vert {0} \rangle}$ and ${\vert {1} \rangle}$ stand for the ground and first excited states of the polariton, respectively. 
