\centering
\includegraphics[scale=0.24]{Fig3}
\caption{(Color online) a) Energy spectrum ($\hbar=1$) of the Hamiltonian~(\ref{HTotal}) for different qubits, as a function of the energy gap of the qubit $2$, $\omega_{q2}=\Delta$. Here, we have considered parameters $\omega_{\rm cav}=1$, $\omega_p=0.8\omega_{\rm cav}$, $g_p=0.3\omega_{\rm cav}$, $\omega_{q1}=0.2\omega_{\rm cav}$, and $g_1=g_2=0.02\omega_{\rm cav}$. Red (squared) lines stand for states with even parity and yellow (continuous) lines stand for states with odd parity. b) First avoided level crossing at the resonance condition $\Delta=0.2\omega_{\rm cav}$. c) Population inversion between states ${\vert {0} \rangle}{\vert {eg} \rangle}$, blue (circle) line, and ${\vert {0} \rangle}{\vert {ge} \rangle}$, red (diamond) line, at the resonance condition $\Delta=0.2\omega_{\rm cav}$. The yellow (continuous) line shows the Von Neumann entropy between the polariton and the two qubits. d) We show the fast oscillations that appear in the population inversion shown in Fig.~\ref{Fig3}(c).}
\label{Fig3}
\end{figure}

The question that we wish to address next concerns whether or not we can use the polariton as a quantum bus or mediator in between the two qubits. In close analogy with the $XY$ interaction mediated by a cavity bus~\cite{Zheng2000,Blais2007,Majer2007}, the polariton should lie at vacuum so that the qubit-qubit interaction appears as a second-order process. This follows from the dispersive interaction between the qubits and the polariton. In order to obtain the effective Hamiltonian~\cite{Suppl}, we consider a dispersive treatment beyond the rotating wave approximation in the qubit-polariton interaction. As compared to the dispersive theory developed in Ref.~\cite{Zueco2009}, we consider the polariton as a whole system and all relevant time scales must be compared to its energy differences, that is, $\omega_{jk}=\omega_j-\omega_k$, where $\omega_j$ is an eigenvalue of the Hamiltonian~(\ref{HPolariton}), that is, $H_p{\vert {j} \rangle}=\hbar\omega_j{\vert {j} \rangle}$. Under such consideration and, by considering the two lowest energy levels of the polariton, ${\vert {0} \rangle}$ and ${\vert {1} \rangle}$, respectively, the effective Hamiltonian that describes an Ising-type qubit-qubit interaction~\cite{Zueco2009,Kurcz2014} reads

Here, $|\chi_{01}|^2=|{\langle {0} \vert}(b+b^\dagger) {\vert {1} \rangle}|^2$, $\hat{Z}_p={\vert {1} \rangle}{\langle {1} \vert}-{\vert {0} \rangle}{\langle {0} \vert}$, $\hat{S}_{12}= g_1 g_2 (1/{\delta^1 _{10}}+1/{\delta^2 _{10}}-1/{\Delta^1 _{10}} -1/{\Delta^2 _{10}})\sigma^x _1 \otimes \sigma^x _2 +\sum_{n=1}^2 2g_n ^2 (\sigma^{+}_n\sigma^{-}_n/{\Delta^n _{10}} -\sigma^{-}_n\sigma^{+}_n/{\delta^n _{10}})$. The detunings $\Delta^n _{10}=\omega_{qn} -\omega_{10}$, $\delta^n _{10}=\omega_{qn} +\omega_{10}$, where $\omega_{qn}$ is the frequency of the $n$th qubit, and $\omega_{10}=\omega_{1}-\omega_{0}$ stands for the polariton gap. In deriving Eq.~(\ref{Heff}), we have considered the rotating-wave approximation so that we neglect fast oscillating terms like $\exp{(i\omega_{kk'}t)}$ with respect to the effective qubit-qubit coupling $J_{\rm eff}=|\chi_{01}|^2 g_1g_2(1/{\delta^1 _{10}}+1/{\delta^2 _{10}}-1/{\Delta^1 _{10}} -1/{\Delta^2 _{10}})/2$, see~\cite{Suppl} for a detailed derivation. 

From the numerical simulations shown in Fig.~\ref{Fig3} using the full Hamiltonian~(\ref{HTotal}), we clearly see a qubit-qubit interaction. In particular, Fig.~\ref{Fig3}(a) shows the energy spectrum of the total system, comprising of a polariton and two qubits, while the qubit $1$ energy gap is fixed at $\omega_{q1}=0.2 \omega_{\text{cav}}$ and the qubit 2 energy gap is tuned from $\omega_{q2} \in [0,1.2]\omega_{\text{cav}}$. If we enlarge the first avoided level crossing of Fig.~\ref{Fig3}(a), at $\Delta=0.2\omega_{\rm cav}$, we arrive at Fig.~\ref{Fig3}(b) where we identify that the two energy levels correspond to states ${\vert {0} \rangle}{\vert {ge} \rangle}$ and ${\vert {0} \rangle}{\vert {eg} \rangle}$. These two states are maximally entangled exactly at the avoided crossing. To show that this is the case, we plot the populations $P_{{\vert {0} \rangle}{\vert {eg} \rangle}}$ and $P_{{\vert {0} \rangle}{\vert {ge} \rangle}}$ as a function of time given that we prepare our state in ${\vert {\bar{\psi}} \rangle}={\vert {0} \rangle}{\vert {ge} \rangle}$. The result is seen in Fig.~\ref{Fig3}(c). The von Neumann entropy, $S(\rho_A)$, between the polariton and the two qubits is also plotted in the same figure. In particular, we see a negligible entanglement between the two subsystems, which guarantees that the polariton is not excited upon qubit-qubit interaction. Furthermore, in Fig.~\ref{Fig3}(c,d) the plots exhibit fast oscillations with respect to the effective qubit-qubit coupling strength. One can show that these fast oscillations have a negligible contribution for the weak qubit-polariton coupling strength, and the dynamics predicted from Hamiltonians~(\ref{HTotal}) and~(\ref{Heff}) matches with high accuracy~\cite{Suppl}.        
