The main advantage of our proposal, namely the polariton mediated quantum information processing, over quantum computing mediated by a single cavity mode~\cite{Zheng2000,Blais2007,Majer2007} is that the gating time for entangling qubits is drastically reduced with  increasing $g_p/\omega_{\rm cav}$ while preserving the $\mathbb{Z}_2$ symmetry. For instance, the circuit QED experiment presented in Ref.~\cite{Majer2007} has demonstrated a qubit-qubit coupling strength of $2J\!\!=\!\!2\pi\times 26~\rm{MHz}$. If we consider the cavity frequency for the ultrastrong coupled system presented in Ref.~\cite{Pol2010}, $\omega_{\rm cav}\!=\!2\pi\times 8~\rm{GHz}$, our model predicts effective qubit-qubit coupling strengths of $J_{\rm eff}\!=\!2\pi\times (21,28,46)~{\rm MHz}$ for $g_p/\omega_{\rm cav}=(0.3,0.4,0.5)$, respectively. These values lead to gating times of $t_{\rm gate}\!=\!\pi/(2J_{\rm eff})\!\approx\! (11,9,5)~{\rm ns}$, which scale similar or better than the time needed to performing a controlled phase with fast and resonant gates in new generation circuit QED setups~\cite{Haack2010,Saira2014}. Moreover, our proposal does not require a tunable qubit-cavity coupling as in the case of circuit QED-based ultrafast gates~\cite{Borja2010,Romero2012}. 
These results establish the features (i), (ii), and (iii) of our proposal, and underline one of the main points of our current work.

From the above results, it is clear the improvement in excitations transfer as one increases the ratio $g_p/\omega_{\rm cav}$. If we consider the dynamics governed by the Hamiltonian~(\ref{HTotal}), in Fig.~\ref{Fig4}(a) we plot the excitation number of the second qubit, $\langle\sigma^{+}_2\sigma^{-}_2\rangle$, as a function of time  for various values of the ratio $g_p/\omega_{\rm cav}$ given that we prepare our system in the state ${\vert {0} \rangle}{\vert {eg} \rangle}$. We see that the larger $g_p/\omega_{\rm cav}$, the faster the rate of excitation transfer. The reason lies with an increase in the matrix element $|\chi_{01}|^2$ with respect to $g_p/\omega_{\rm cav}$, as shown in Fig.~\ref{Fig4}(b). 

{\em Nonequilibrium steady state.---}Before we have discussed how our model allows us to improve both the gating time for entangling qubits and for transferring a single excitation between them, we begin with the study of the steady-state excitation transferred to the qubit $2$ as the qubit $1$ is incoherently pumped at rate $\gamma_p$. This is motivated by recent developments in cavity-enhanced transport of excitons~\cite{Pupillo2015} in disordered systems, and our aim is to provide the first step towards polariton-enhanced transport of excitations. Here, we will include the spontaneous emission of the qubit $2$, and loss mechanisms in the polariton.
\begin{figure}[b]
\centering
\includegraphics[scale=0.46]{Fig5}
\caption{(Color online) Steady-state excitation number for the qubit $2$. In this simulation we have considered $\omega_{\rm cav}=1$, $\omega_{q1}=\omega_{q2}=0.2\omega_{\rm cav}$, $\omega_p=0.8\omega_{\rm cav}$, $g_1=g_2=10^{-2}\omega_{\rm cav}$. The bare loss and pump ratios are $\gamma_{\rm pump}=\gamma_x=\gamma_z=\gamma_{\rm cav}=10^{-2}\omega_{\rm cav}$, and $\gamma_{\rm out}=10^{-1}\omega_{\rm cav}$. We have verified that a Fock space of $N=8$ is enough to assure convergence for each value of the ratio $g_p/\omega_{\rm cav}$.}
\label{Fig5}
\end{figure}

Since our system described by the Hamiltonian~(\ref{HTotal}) has a large anharmonicity, we need to take into account the coloured nature of baths by means of the time-convolutionless projection operator method~\cite{DeLiberato2009}. The dynamics is governed by the master equation $\dot{\rho}=-i[H,\rho]+\mathcal{L}(\rho)$ ($\hbar=1$), where $\rho$ is the density matrix and $H$ is the Hamiltonian~(\ref{HTotal}). The Liouvillian $\mathcal{L}(\rho)=\sum_n(U_n\rho S_n+S_n\rho U^{\dag}_n-S_nU_n\rho-\rho U^{\dag}_nS_n)$ includes operators $S_{x_1}=\sigma^x_1$ for the incoherent pumping acting on qubit $1$ ($\gamma_{\rm pump}$), and $S_{x_2}=\sigma^x_2$ for the spontaneous emission of qubit $2$ ($\gamma_{\rm out}$). Moreover, we include loss mechanisms acting on the polariton via transversal noise ($\gamma_x$), longitudinal noise ($\gamma_z$), and noise acting on the field quadrature ($\gamma_{\rm cav}$), through operators $S_{x_3}=\sigma^x_3$, $S_{z_3}=\sigma^z_3$, and $S_{q}=b + b^{\dag}$, respectively. In our treatment, each loss/pump mechanism is described by independent thermal baths with bare loss/pump rates $\gamma_j$. See~\cite{Suppl} for a detailed description of the master equation.    

The steady-state solution to the master equation is solved numerically by means of the superspace method discussed in Ref.~\cite{Navarrete2015}. Figure~\ref{Fig5} shows the steady-state excitation transferred to the qubit $2$ ($\langle\sigma^{+}_2\sigma^{-}_2\rangle_{\rm ss}$) while the qubit $1$ experiences incoherent pumping as the coupling strength of the polariton enters the ultrastrong coupling regime, $0.1\lesssim g_p/\omega_{\rm cav}<1$. The figure shows a striking increase of $2$ order of magnitude in the excitation number as the ratio $g_p/\omega_{\rm cav}$ ranges from $10^{-2}$ (strong coupling regime) to $0.8$ (USC regime). This result establishes the feature (iv), and underlines the second major point of our work. 


{\em Conclusions.---}We have analyzed the equilibrium and nonequilibrium properties of two qubits interacting with an ultrastrong coupled qubit-cavity system or polariton, and we have demonstrated the abilities of the polariton as a quantum bus to mediate an Ising-type interaction between qubits. In particular, we have shown that the time for entangling qubits increases as the qubit-cavity coupling strength in the polariton increases. The entangling gate is performed by simply biasing the qubits energy gap and for fixed polariton parameters, thus overcoming the problem of tunable qubit-cavity coupling. We stress that the manipulation of the qubits energy gap does not introduce any symmetry breaking mechanism, and thus the ${\mathbb{Z}}_2$ symmetry is preserved. Moreover, we have demonstrated improvement in the rate of excitations transfer to qubit 2 when $g_p/\omega_{\text{cav}}$ is increased and  the qubit 1 is incoherently pumped. We reiterate that our proposal might pave the way for multipurpose parity protected quantum information with a polariton bus, and it might serve as a building block for the cavity-enhanced excitons transport in disordered many-body systems.

